tamin B12 (cobalamin) absorption is a complex process requiring multiple steps:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDietary B12 is released from proteins by gastric acid\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIntrinsic factor is secreted by gastric parietal cells\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn the \u003Cstrong\u003Eduodenum\u003C/strong\u003E, B12 binds to intrinsic factor\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe complex travels through the \u003Cstrong\u003Ejejunum\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESpecific receptors in the \u003Cstrong\u003Eileum\u003C/strong\u003E absorb the B12-intrinsic factor complex\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Edescending colon\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Erectum\u003C/strong\u003E do not participate in B12 absorption\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis process explains why conditions affecting the stomach (lack of intrinsic factor) or ileum can cause B12 deficiency. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Vitamin B12 (cobalamin) is absorbed in the ileum via intrinsic factor-mediated transport.","Intrinsic factor is produced by gastric parietal cells and binds to B12 in the duodenum.","The vitamin B12-intrinsic factor complex is absorbed by specific receptors in the ileal mucosa."],"references":["Milman N. Intestinal absorption of folic acid - new physiologic \u0026 molecular aspects. Indian J Med Res. 2012 Nov;136(5):725-8. PMID: 23287118; PMCID: PMC3573592.","Thomson AB, Keelan M, Thiesen A, Clandinin MT, Ropeleski M, Wild GE. Small bowel review: diseases of the small intestine. Dig Dis Sci. 2001 Dec;46(12):2555-66. doi: 10.1023/a:1012782321827. PMID: 11768246.","Gu\u00e9ant JL, Gu\u00e9ant-Rodriguez RM, Alpers DH. Vitamin B12 absorption and malabsorption. Vitam Horm. 2022;119:241-274. doi: 10.1016/bs.vh.2022.01.016. Epub 2022 Mar 1. PMID: 35337622.","Basile EJ, Launico MV, Sheer AJ. Physiology, Nutrient Absorption. [Updated 2023 Oct 28]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK597379/","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50579"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15235"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50579","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50579"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-25T15:45:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-25T15:45:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7926"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65143"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)",